<ArticleLayout
  title="How to Choose the Right Dog Bed for Your Home"
  description="Choose a dog bed by watching how the dog sleeps, measuring the resting position and planning for washing, climate and the floor space it will occupy."
  category="Pets"
  date="Updated July 2026"
  readingTime="9 minute read"
  image="/images/pet.webp"
  imageAlt="A calm pet-friendly living room with a washable dog bed near warm natural light"
>
  <p>
    The dog has a vote in where a bed succeeds. A beautifully sized cushion may be ignored if it
    sits in an exposed walkway, feels too warm or does not allow the animal to stretch in its usual
    sleeping position.
  </p>
  <p>
    Watch where and how the dog rests, then measure that posture rather than relying only on breed
    labels. Consider the intended floor, household temperature and how the cover and filling will
    be cleaned and dried.
  </p>
  <p>
    Place a taped outline in the proposed spot before buying. For mobility, pain, allergy or other
    health concerns, ask the animal's veterinarian which features matter for that individual dog.
  </p>

  <h2>The Dog Has to Choose the Bed Too</h2>
  <p>
    The right dog bed is the one your dog will actually use and your household can
    realistically maintain. For many homes, that means choosing the correct size, a washable
    cover, enough support for the dog's age and weight, and a shape that fits the room
    without becoming a nuisance.
  </p>
  <p>
    A more expensive bed is not automatically better if it is hard to clean, too warm, too
    bulky or placed somewhere the dog does not like resting. In some cases, a simpler,
    washable mat or a lower-cost option makes more sense than a large decorative bed that
    suits the room but not the dog.
  </p>

  <h2>Watch Where and How the Dog Sleeps</h2>
  <p>
    Watch your dog for a few days before choosing a bed. Dogs often show clear preferences:
    some curl tightly, some stretch out, some lean into furniture, some burrow under blankets
    and some move from room to room depending on light, temperature and household activity.
  </p>
  <p>Common sleeping habits can point towards different bed shapes:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Curled sleepers may suit round beds, donut-style beds or beds with soft sides.</li>
    <li>Stretch-out sleepers usually need rectangular or mat-style beds with extra length.</li>
    <li>Dogs that lean into furniture may like a bolster or raised side.</li>
    <li>Dogs that move between rooms may suit a lightweight mat or a second simple bed.</li>
    <li>Dogs that sleep hot may prefer breathable fabrics or raised designs.</li>
    <li>Dogs that burrow may like softer sides or a blanket, as long as it can be washed.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    This step can prevent wasted spending. A bed that looks cosy online may be wrong for a
    dog that sprawls across the floor every night.
  </p>

  <h2>Measure your dog before choosing a bed</h2>
  <p>
    Product photos can make beds look larger than they are. Before buying, measure your dog
    in the position it uses most often. For dogs that stretch out, measure from nose to base
    of tail, or use the full stretched length if that is how the dog usually sleeps. Add
    extra room so the dog is not hanging off the edge.
  </p>
  <p>When comparing bed sizes, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>The internal sleeping surface, not only the outside dimensions.</li>
    <li>Whether bolsters or raised sides reduce the usable flat area.</li>
    <li>The manufacturer's height and weight guidance if provided.</li>
    <li>Whether your dog can turn around comfortably.</li>
    <li>Whether the bed still suits the space once placed in the room.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    For larger breeds, usable sleeping surface matters more than the overall footprint. A
    large bolster bed can look generous but leave less flat space than a simpler rectangular
    mat.
  </p>

  <h2>Common dog bed types and where they work best</h2>
  <p>
    Different bed types solve different problems. None is automatically better for every dog
    or every home.
  </p>
  <p>
    Flat mats are useful for crates, laundries, cars and dogs that like to stretch out. They
    are often easier to move and wash, but may feel less cosy than a padded bed with sides.
  </p>
  <p>
    Bolster beds suit dogs that like leaning or feeling enclosed. The trade-off is that the
    side padding reduces the flat sleeping area and can make the bed bulkier in small rooms.
  </p>
  <p>
    Donut or round beds may suit curled sleepers, especially smaller dogs, but they may be
    frustrating for dogs that sprawl or shift positions often.
  </p>
  <p>
    Orthopaedic-style beds may be worth considering for older or heavier dogs, but avoid
    relying on the label alone. Compare the actual support, thickness, cover quality and size.
    If your dog has pain, arthritis, injury, mobility issues or persistent sleep problems,
    speak with a vet.
  </p>
  <p>
    Raised beds can help with airflow in warmer rooms, tiled spaces and verandah-adjacent
    areas. They can also be easier to sweep underneath. They may feel less enclosed, take more
    room and may not suit every dog.
  </p>
  <p>
    Waterproof or water-resistant beds can help around puppies, older dogs or outdoor-adjacent
    areas, but check whether the cover is still comfortable, washable and practical to dry.
    Water-resistant does not always mean easy to maintain.
  </p>

  <h2>Material, fill and support: what to compare</h2>
  <p>
    Marketing language can make dog beds sound more technical than they are. In practice,
    foam thickness, fill quality, cover design and cleaning access often matter more.
  </p>
  <p>Before choosing a material or fill, compare:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Whether the bed has enough depth for the dog's weight.</li>
    <li>Whether very soft filling may flatten quickly.</li>
    <li>Whether the cover is removable or spot-clean only.</li>
    <li>Whether slippery fabric may move on tiles or timber floors.</li>
    <li>Whether plush fabric may hold hair, dust, grass seeds or odour.</li>
    <li>Whether canvas-style fabric is durable enough without being too rough.</li>
    <li>Whether a waterproof liner may feel noisy or warm.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    For dogs with health, skin, allergy or mobility issues, seek veterinary advice rather than
    relying on a product description.
  </p>

  <h2>Cleaning and odour control matter more than people expect</h2>
  <p>
    A dog bed lives with hair, drool, mud, sand, grass seeds, food crumbs and everyday
    household dust. In warm rooms or humid weather, bedding that cannot dry properly can
    become unpleasant quickly.
  </p>
  <p>Practical cleaning checks include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Whether the cover removes easily.</li>
    <li>Whether the cover is machine washable.</li>
    <li>Whether the whole bed fits in your washing machine if required.</li>
    <li>How long the cover or insert takes to dry.</li>
    <li>Whether hair brushes or vacuums off the fabric.</li>
    <li>Whether spare covers are available.</li>
    <li>Whether wet or muddy dogs will use the bed often.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Beds near back doors, laundries or verandah-adjacent spaces need easier cleaning than a
    bed used only in a calm bedroom corner. Dark colours can hide marks, but they do not hide
    odour. Light colours show dirt sooner, which can be useful if it prompts regular washing.
  </p>
  <p>
    If cleaning is already the hard part of living with pets, our{" "}
    <a href="/guides/pet-cleaning-supplies-what-to-check-before-buying-cleaning-gear/">pet cleaning supplies guide</a>{" "}
    can help you plan around hair, mud and odour.
  </p>

  <h2>Choosing a bed for puppies, older dogs and heavy chewers</h2>
  <p>
    Puppies can chew, toilet on beds and outgrow bedding quickly. A lower-cost washable
    option may make more sense early on than a large premium bed that gets destroyed or
    outgrown before the dog settles into its adult size.
  </p>
  <p>
    Older dogs may need easier entry, lower edges, stable placement and firmer support. Avoid
    high bolsters if the dog struggles to step in. If age, pain, arthritis, injury or mobility
    issues affect sleep, movement or comfort, speak with a vet.
  </p>
  <p>
    Heavy chewers need close supervision and durable construction, but no dog bed is truly
    indestructible. Loose stuffing, zips, torn fabric and detached parts can become hazards.
    If chewing is persistent or destructive, consider training advice or veterinary guidance
    rather than assuming a tougher bed will solve the behaviour.
  </p>
  <p>
    For broader first-home setup, see{" "}
    <a href="/guides/new-puppy-essentials/">New Puppy Essentials</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Where the bed will sit in your home</h2>
  <p>
    Bed placement can matter as much as the bed itself. A dog may ignore a bed if it is too
    isolated, too hot, too noisy or too far from the household. A bed may also be impractical
    if it blocks a walkway or sits where people constantly step around it.
  </p>
  <p>Think about common locations:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Living room: keep the bed out of walkways but close enough for social dogs.</li>
    <li>Bedroom: consider size, warmth, fabric noise and cleaning access.</li>
    <li>Laundry: practical for washable zones, but it may be cold, noisy or isolated.</li>
    <li>Kitchen or dining area: useful for social dogs if the fabric handles crumbs and spills.</li>
    <li>Apartment: compact sizing, odour control and easy washing matter.</li>
    <li>Rental home: avoid beds that mark floors, trap moisture or need permanent fixtures.</li>
    <li>Tiled floors: consider a non-slip base or stable mat underneath.</li>
    <li>Timber floors: think about scratching, trapped moisture and sliding.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    In homes with children, place the bed where the dog can rest without being constantly
    disturbed. A bed should support household routines, not become another source of friction.
    For rental-specific planning, see{" "}
    <a href="/guides/rental-friendly-pet-setup-what-to-check-before-buying-pet-gear/">A Pet Setup for Rentals That Protects the Home</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Where Comfort, Cleaning and Floor Space Conflict</h2>
  <p>
    Dog beds usually involve trade-offs. A very soft bed may feel cosy but be harder to wash.
    A large bed may suit a sprawling dog but crowd a small living room. A raised bed may be
    cooler in summer but less snug in winter.
  </p>
  <p>Common trade-offs include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Soft and cosy versus easy to clean.</li>
    <li>Large and comfortable versus bulky in small rooms.</li>
    <li>Raised and breathable versus less enclosed.</li>
    <li>Cheap and replaceable versus better support and longer use.</li>
    <li>Stylish fabric versus practical washable fabric.</li>
    <li>Bolsters for comfort versus reduced sleeping surface.</li>
    <li>Waterproof protection versus warmth, noise and comfort.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The right choice depends on the dog, the room and how much maintenance the household can
    realistically keep up with.
  </p>

  <h2>Test the Bed Size in Its Intended Place</h2>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Measure your dog in its usual sleeping position.</li>
    <li>Check internal sleeping dimensions, not just outside dimensions.</li>
    <li>Confirm the cover is removable and washable.</li>
    <li>Check whether the insert is protected.</li>
    <li>Think about drying time in wet or humid weather.</li>
    <li>Check whether the bed will slide on your flooring.</li>
    <li>Decide where the bed will sit before buying.</li>
    <li>Consider whether your dog chews, digs, sheds heavily or gets wet often.</li>
    <li>Avoid high sides if your dog struggles to step in.</li>
    <li>Check whether replacement covers are available.</li>
    <li>Avoid buying only for colour or room styling.</li>
    <li>For health, mobility, allergy or pain concerns, speak with a vet.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Why Dog Beds Go Unused</h2>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Buying too small because the product photo looks generous.</li>
    <li>Ignoring the difference between outside dimensions and usable sleeping space.</li>
    <li>Choosing a spot-clean-only bed for a dog that gets wet, sandy or muddy.</li>
    <li>Assuming an orthopaedic-style label means the bed suits every older dog.</li>
    <li>Buying a bulky bed before deciding where it will go.</li>
    <li>Choosing plush fabric for a dog that brings in grass seeds, mud or sand.</li>
    <li>Buying an expensive puppy bed that may be chewed or outgrown quickly.</li>
    <li>Forgetting how warm the room gets in summer.</li>
    <li>Forgetting that bolsters reduce usable sleeping space.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Match the Bed to the Dog and the Room</h2>
  <p>
    If you are comparing product types later, keep the decision tied to suitability rather
    than chasing the most expensive option.
  </p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>For small dogs: compact beds with washable covers and enough side support if they like curling up.</li>
    <li>For medium dogs: rectangular beds can be flexible if the dog changes positions.</li>
    <li>For large dogs: focus on usable sleeping area, support and whether the cover can realistically be washed.</li>
    <li>For older dogs: lower entry, firmer support and stable placement matter more than decorative shape.</li>
    <li>For warm homes: breathable fabrics or raised designs may be worth considering.</li>
    <li>For messy dogs: removable covers, water-resistant liners and quick-drying materials matter.</li>
    <li>For apartments: odour control, compact sizing and easy washing are priorities.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A product type is only useful if it suits the dog and the home. If the dog already has a
    washable mat it uses happily, delaying a new purchase may be the better decision.
  </p>

  <h2>Choose for Sleep and Washing, Not Styling</h2>
  <p>
    Choosing a dog bed well is about matching the bed to the dog and the household, not
    chasing the most expensive or most attractive option. A practical bed that is the right
    size, easy to clean, comfortable enough and placed in the right spot is usually a better
    buy than one chosen only for looks.
  </p>
  <p>
    Watch sleep habits, measure carefully, think about cleaning and choose a bed that
    will work in the room every day. That is what turns a dog bed from a decorative purchase
    into a useful part of the home.
  </p>

